  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Evelina A. S. Smith is living in an anti-slavery desert and yearns for abolition sympathy. She has tried all kinds of people, &quot;but they talk a different language or they say nothing.&quot; She wishes that she might always feel &quot;the faith and hope that seems to shine in Mrs. Follen&apos;s countenance and conversation.&quot; Evelina A. S. Smith&apos;s illness kept her from attending the annual meeting. She tells of Mr. Increase S. Smith&apos;s confining occupations. She admires William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s &quot;piece&quot; on a free press. C. L. Remond delivered two fine lectures here, but they were attended by next to nobody. She asks if Sydney [Howard Gay] is enjoying the honeymoon. Evelina A. S. Smith has been reading Gibbons and she is attending a history class and studying German. Evelina A. S. Smith believes &quot;the early Christians were very much like the non-resistants and come outers of the present time modified somewhat by the spirit of the age, but my friends here, know nothing real[l]y of non-resistants or come outers.&quot;</subfield>
